Ontario School Information and Student Demographics¶

Data Visualizations of EQAO Assessements 2022-2023¶

Data Source: Ontario Data Catalogue

Introduction¶

Understanding the educational landscape is important for policymakers, educators, and researchers alike, particularly in regions as diverse and populous as Ontario, Canada. Leveraging the dataset provided by the Ontario Ministry of Education, which encompasses school information and student demographics, this web page aims to provide the relevant data visualizations on the academic achievement of elementary and secondary students in Ontario, focusing on reading, writing, and mathematics performances. It also provides data visualizations on the correlation of the students' academic achievements with socio-economic factors, like geographic location, household income, first languages, and parents' educational attainment. This could help in analyzing trends and variations in performance and provide insights into the effectiveness of educational policies and practices in addressing learning outcomes. It could also help in identifying potential barriers to educational attainment that could help in coming up with targeted interventions that promote equity and inclusivity in Ontario's education system.

Education Quality and Accountability Office (EQAO)¶

The EQAO, established in 1996, is an independent agency of the Government of Ontario, Canada. The primary role of EQAO is to assess the quality of education in Ontario's publicly funded schools. It conducts province-wide assessments of student achievement in key areas such as reading, writing, mathematics, and secondary school literacy. By administering standardized tests to students across the province, EQAO aims to evaluate proficiency levels, inform educational policies, and drive improvements in teaching and learning practices.

School Information and Student Demographics Dataset¶

The School Information and Student Demographics dataset is accessible through the Ontario Data Catalog.

The figure below provides a general overview of the entire data set. Of particular interest are schools in the elementary and secondary level in Ontario. Elementary schools in Ontario vary in their Grade Ranges - JK-8, 7-8, JK-6, JK-2, 1-8, JK-3, 4-8, 6-8, JK-4, 5-8, JK-5, K-8, K-6, K-5, K-7, 1-5, 1-6. Grade levels in secondary schools include 9-12 and 11-12. Elementary and secondary Schools can also fall in one of the following types - Public, Catholic, Hospital, Protestant Separate, and Provincial. The figure also shows the District School Boards that participated in the EQAO assessment tests in elementary and OSSLT in secondary, along with the school counts.

Schools with non-numeric entries such as 'N/D', 'N/R', 'S.', and null values, as well as those with values of 0 or less, have been excluded. School Geographic Location¶

Geographic location has long been a topic of interest in educational research, as it is often associated with differences in socioeconomic status, access to resources, and educational opportunities. Understanding the role of geographic location in student achievement is crucial for identifying disparities in educational outcomes for targeted interventions to promote equity and inclusivity in the education system.

Each colored dot in the map represents a school.

Percentage of Students: Percentage of students achieving the provincial standard in Reading. 0.5 would mean 50% of assessed students achieved the provincial standard. 1 would mean 100% of assessed students achived the provincial standard.
